Strategy
When dealing with strategy, one could legitimately discuss everything that has been written about organizations (Starbuck 1965).
To reduce ambiguity and consolidate the views on strategy, Mintzberg (2000), e.g., has offered five different perspectives of strategy:


A plan; a direction of how to get from here to there;
A pattern if consistent behavior over time;
A position, created by a different set of activities and typically results in a unique set of products in particular markets;
A perspective; the fundamental way of doing things;
A play; a deception, a specific manourvre intended to outwit an opponent or competitor.


Porter described strategy as the creation of a unique and valuable position, involving a different set of activities (Porter et al. 1996).

Project portfolios
A project portfolio is a collection of projects, programs1, and subsidiary portfolios as a group to achieve strategic objectives.1 A program is a group of related projects managed in a coordinated way to obtain benefits and control not available from managing them individually (PMI 2017b).
The components of a portfolio


are driven by the organization’s strategic goals and objectives;
represent investments made or planned;
are quantifiable (e.g., can be categorized, evaluated, prioritized, authorized);
may be independent or interdependent;
may have related or unrelated objectives;
compete for a share of some or all of a set of limited resources.

